summary:
I am an ambitious, enthusiastic, critical, and  driven researcher with strong analytical, technical, and problem solving skills. 
Throughout my PhD, I coached and mentored several students and collaborated with several national and international academic and industrial partners. I was responsible for the organization, planning, and execution of an European Union-funded projected involving four different international scientific departments. Furthermore, I have a big heart for science communication both written (manuscripts, reviews, animal ethical licenses, grants, and grant reporting) and oral (congress attendance and scientific meetings) in the academic setting, but I also love to explain my work to the general public (pint of science speaker and organizer). I like to work in teams, however, I like to take leadership and perform tasks an efficient manner. I am always eager to learn and together with my dedication and accuracy, I aim to execute projects in the most perfect manner.

During my PhD, I developed transferable skills, including project and time management, leadership (leading multiple multicenter projects), organization (set up new collaborations), coaching (supervising students), decision making, oral (presentation at scientific meetings and congresses) and written (manuscripts, reviews, reporting, grants, ethical documents) communication, team work, and problem solving skills.

Currently, treatments for NPC disease are scarce and the major problem is that the drugs can not pass through the blood-brain barrier.
